.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Baroness","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Norwegian: old variant of <b>Bartnes</b> (and, in North America, probably also an altered form of this), a habitational name from Trøndelag, a form of Old Norse <i>burkn</i> ‘fern’ + <i>nes</i> ‘promontary, headland’.","In some cases possibly also an altered form of German   Bartmess  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bartmess","meanings":["American shortened form of German   Barthelmess  ."]}]},{"name":"Adeliza","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Corrupted from Adelaide"],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Baroness Adeliza de Beaumont was born about 1034, in Beaumont-les-Nonains, Oise, Picardie, France. She married Robert de Umfreville about 1060, in Amfréville, Manche, Normandy, France. She died in 1120, in Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 87."},"et":{"ABT 1034–1120":"umbes 1034–1120","1030–1086":"1030–1086","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1060–1145":"1060–1145","1067–1122":"1067–1122","1069–Male":"1069–Surnud","1034–1120":"1034–1120","1090":"1090","ABT 1034":"umbes 1034","1069":"1069","abt 1060":"umbes 1060","1145":"1145","1034":"1034","1067":"1067","1122":"1122","1120":"1120","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","Forest Vale, Redsedale, Northumberland, England":"Ridsdale, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Amfreville, Normandy, France, France":"Amfrév